04219nam a2200601Ia 9781501723643DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20181995nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017236437 a10.7591/97815017236432doi  a(DE-B1597)514780  a(OCoLC)1083586986  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aQL391.S5bC87 1994eb 7aSCI0700202bisacsh04a595.1/722304aThe Sipuncula :bTheir Systematics, Biology, and Evolution /ced. by Edward B. Cutler. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©1995  a1 online resource (480 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChecklist of the Sipunculan Species -- tIntroduction -- tGlossary -- tPart I. Systematics -- tPart II. Sipunculan Biology: A Review -- tPart III. Zoogeography and Evolution -- tAppendix 1. Recent Species lnquirenda and lncertae Sedis -- tAppendix 2. Species lnquirenda and lncertae Sedis as in Stephen and Edmonds, 1972, with Current Status -- tBibliography -- tTaxonomic Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Sipuncula, a group of ocean-dwelling worms related to annelids and mollusks, play a significant role in the bioerosion of coral reefs and are useful indicators of environmental conditions. The 155 species live in a wide variety ofmarine habitats at all depths, in sand and mud, in burrows in soft rock and dead coral, and inside such protective shelters as mollusk shells. Important food items for fish and invertebrate predators, they also recycle organic wastes and function as bioassay tools for human diseases such as cystic fibrosis and acute cholera. Edward B. Cutler brings together in this volume everything that is known about the entire phylum.An introduction, with practical information about collecting and handling the animals, is followed by Part One, which incorporates new systematic analyses made during the past twenty years and offers illustrated keys to all taxa, replacing the work of A.C. Stephen and S.J. Edmonds. Part Two reviews the past thirty years' work in such areas as ecology, muscular sysetms, blood chemistry, respiration, reproduction, and excretion. Part Three provides a new synthetic perspective on the phylum's zoogeography and evolutionary relationships, both to other phyla and within the phylum. It utilizes information from the fossil record, paleo-oceanographic data, and comparative studies of immunology, physiology, embryology, and anatomy.Edward B. Cutler is Professor of Biology at Utica College of Syracuse University, now on long-term leave at the Museum of Comparative Zoology, Harvard University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aSipuncula. 4aGeneral Science. 4aNature Guides & Natural History. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Zoology / Invertebrates.2bisacsh1 aCutler, Edward B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172364340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501723643423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501723643/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles